First solution:
to fix notation, let $firstarea$ be the area
of region $pointdelta pointecho pointfoxtrot pointgolf$, and $secondarea$ be the area of $pointdelta pointecho pointindia pointhotel$; further
let $sectorarea$ denote the area of sector $originpoint pointdelta pointecho$, which only depends on the
arc length of $quadrantarc$.  If $[XYZ]$ denotes the area of triangle
$[XYZ]$, then we have
$firstarea = sectorarea + [originpoint pointecho pointgolf] - [originpoint pointdelta pointfoxtrot]$ and $secondarea = sectorarea + [originpoint pointdelta pointhotel] - [originpoint pointecho pointindia]$.  But
clearly $[originpoint pointecho pointgolf] = [originpoint pointecho pointindia]$ and $[originpoint pointdelta pointfoxtrot] = [originpoint pointdelta pointhotel]$, and so
$firstarea + secondarea = 2\,sectorarea$.

\begin{center}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\draw (0,0) circle (2);
\draw (0,2) -- (0,0) -- (2,0);
\draw (1.732,0) -- (1.732,1) -- (0,1);
\draw (.7,0) -- (.7,1.873) -- (0,1.873);
\draw (1.732,1) -- (0,0) -- (.7,1.873);
\draw (0,0) node[anchor=north east] {$originpoint$};
\draw (.7,0) node[anchor=north] {$pointfoxtrot$};
\draw (1.732,0) node[anchor=north] {$pointgolf$};
\draw (1.732,1) node[anchor=south west] {$pointecho$};
\draw (.7,1.873) node[anchor=south west] {$pointdelta$};
\draw (0,1) node[anchor=east] {$pointindia$};
\draw (0,1.7) node[anchor=east] {$pointhotel$};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{center}

Second solution: We may parametrize a point in $quadrantarc$ by any of
$horizcoord$, $vertcoord$, or $angleparam = \tan^{-1} (vertcoord/horizcoord)$.  Then $firstarea$ and $secondarea$ are
just the integrals of $vertcoord\,dhorizcoord$ and $horizcoord\,dvertcoord$ over the appropriate
intervals; thus $firstarea+secondarea$ is the integral of $horizcoord\,dvertcoord - vertcoord\,dhorizcoord$
(minus because the limits of integration are reversed).
But $dangleparam = horizcoord\,dvertcoord - vertcoord\,dhorizcoord$, and so $firstarea+secondarea = \Delta angleparam$
is precisely the radian measure of $quadrantarc$. (Of course, one can perfectly well
do this problem by computing the two integrals
separately. But what's the fun in that?)

