Second solution: We may parametrize a point in $horizonex$ by any of
$paradoxer$, $labyrinth$, or $ignition = \tan^{-1} (labyrinth/paradoxer)$.  Then $nebulasix$ and $galactus$ are
just the integrals of $labyrinth\,dparadoxer$ and $paradoxer\,dlabyrinth$ over the appropriate
intervals; thus $nebulasix+galactus$ is the integral of $paradoxer\,dlabyrinth - labyrinth\,dparadoxer$
(minus because the limits of integration are reversed).
But $dignition = paradoxer\,dlabyrinth - labyrinth\,dparadoxer$, and so $nebulasix+galactus = \Delta ignition$
is precisely the radian measure of $horizonex$. (Of course, one can perfectly well
do this problem by computing the two integrals
separately. But what's the fun in that?)

descriptive_long_misleading.solution:
First solution:
to fix notation, let $perimeter$ be the area
of region $nonpointdnonpointenonpointfnonpointg$, and $circumference$ be the area of $nonpointdnonpointenonpointinonpointh$; further
let $anglemeasure$ denote the area of sector $nonpointononpointdnonpointe$, which only depends on the
arc length of $straightline$.  If $[XYZ]$ denotes the area of triangle
$[XYZ]$, then we have
$perimeter = anglemeasure + [nonpointononpointenonpointg] - [nonpointononpointdnonpointf]$ and $circumference = anglemeasure + [nonpointononpointdnonpointh] - [nonpointononpointenonpointi]$.  But
clearly $[nonpointononpointenonpointg] = [nonpointononpointenonpointi]$ and $[nonpointononpointdnonpointf] = [nonpointononpointdnonpointh]$, and so
$perimeter + circumference = 2anglemeasure$.

\begin{center}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\draw (0,0) circle (2);
\draw (0,2) -- (0,0) -- (2,0);
\draw (1.732,0) -- (1.732,1) -- (0,1);
\draw (.7,0) -- (.7,1.873) -- (0,1.873);
\draw (1.732,1) -- (0,0) -- (.7,1.873);
\draw (0,0) node[anchor=north east] {$nonpointo$};
\draw (.7,0) node[anchor=north] {$nonpointf$};
\draw (1.732,0) node[anchor=north] {$nonpointg$};
\draw (1.732,1) node[anchor=south west] {$nonpointe$};
\draw (.7,1.873) node[anchor=south west] {$nonpointd$};
\draw (0,1) node[anchor=east] {$nonpointi$};
\draw (0,1.7) node[anchor=east] {$nonpointh$};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{center}

Second solution: We may parametrize a point in $straightline$ by any of
$verticalcoord$, $horizontalcoord$, or $linearparam = \tan^{-1} (horizontalcoord/verticalcoord)$.  Then $perimeter$ and $circumference$ are
just the integrals of $horizontalcoord\,dverticalcoord$ and $verticalcoord\,dhorizontalcoord$ over the appropriate
intervals; thus $perimeter+circumference$ is the integral of $verticalcoord\,dhorizontalcoord - horizontalcoord\,dverticalcoord$
(minus because the limits of integration are reversed).
But $dlinearparam = verticalcoord\,dhorizontalcoord - horizontalcoord\,dverticalcoord$, and so $perimeter+circumference = \Delta linearparam$
is precisely the radian measure of $straightline$. (Of course, one can perfectly well
do this problem by computing the two integrals
separately. But what's the fun in that?)

